Onset detection¶

An onset is the point in time at which an event begins.
In the context of a drum beat, each individual hit on the drum could be considered an onset.

Onset in time domain, from "A Tutorial on Onset Detection in Music Signals" by Juan Pablo Bello et al.
retrieved from: http://www.eecs.qmul.ac.uk/former/people/jbc/Documents/Bello-TSAP-2005.pdf

How to locate onsets?¶

one way is to locate the envlope peaks in the signal time domain. this process will be achieved is follows:

  1. signal envelop calculation - find the local max of using rolling window.
  2. peaks detection - finding peaks that are higher than the .85 quantile of the envelope amplitude.
In [218]:
def amplitude_envlope(x, frame_size=1024, step_size=128):
    return np.array([x[i:i+frame_size].max() for i in range(0, len(x), step_size)])
In [219]:
frame_size = 512
step_size = 128

# calculate the envlope of the signal
x_env = amplitude_envlope(x, frame_size, step_size)

# creating a time vector for the x-axis, using librosa frames_to_time
frames = range(len(x_env))
t = librosa.frames_to_time(frames, hop_length=step_size)

# finding peaks indices, and converting them to time indices (sample * step_size/sample_rate)
onset_frames = scipy.signal.find_peaks(x_env, height=np.quantile(x_env, .85))[0]
onset_times = np.dot(onset_frames, step_size/sr)

Plot¶

In [221]:
# plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
librosa.display.waveshow(x, alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(t, x_env, color="r")
for x_i in onset_times:
    plt.axvline(x=x_i, color='g')
plt.ylim((-1, 1))
plt.title("audio signal + envelope + peaks")
plt.show()
In [222]:
n0, n1 = 4*sr, int(4.2*sr)
y = x[n0:n1]

# calculate the envlope of the signal
x_env = amplitude_envlope(y, frame_size, step_size)

# creating a time vector for the x-axis, using librosa frames_to_time
frames = range(len(x_env))
t = librosa.frames_to_time(frames, hop_length=step_size)

# finding peaks indices, and converting them to time indices (sample * step_size/sample_rate)
peaks_frames = scipy.signal.find_peaks(x_env, height=np.quantile(x_env, .85))[0]
peaks_times = np.dot(peaks_frames, step_size/sr)

# plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
librosa.display.waveshow(y, alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(t, x_env, color="r")
for x_i in peaks_times:
    plt.axvline(x=x_i, color='g')
plt.ylim((-1, 1))
plt.title(f"audio signal + envelope + peaks in from sec 4 to sec 4.2")
plt.show()
